{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254632/1930073001/0016.xml":{"full_text":"16\nSHIFT IN POPULATION TO GIVE QTIES CONTROL IN ELECTIONS\nRATIO OF URBAN\nTO RURAL MAT\nBEGO-40\nFinal Returns Slated to Show\nBiggest Shift in History as\nIndustry Attracts Surplus\nThe mpst pronounced shift in\npopulation from country to town\nand city in the nation\u2019s history\nWill be shown in the 1930 census,\nit was predicted today on the\nbasis of preliminary returns to\nthe Census Bureau.\nThe official figures will reveal\na trend apparent with rapid in\ndustralization of the United\nStates in the last decade, and\nWill be a basis for reapportlon-\nOient of the national House of\nRepresentatives. They also will\nmean a change in the Electoral\nCollege, which equals member\nship in Congress, and will force\nrealignment of State legislative\ndistrk'\nM-40, Cities Lead\nThe ratio of urban and rural\npopulation may reach 60-40 in\nthe 1930 census\u20146o per cent of\nthe people living in urban cen\nters. classed as towns of 2,500\ndr more, to 40 per cent in the\ncountry.\nDuring almost the entire his\ntory of the nation the \u201cfarm\nvote\u201d of the nation has been\nsupreme. In 1920 for the first\ntime more than one-half the peo\nple lived in urban centers. But\nt|o reapportionments were made\non that basis. After the im\npending realignment of political\nrepresentation, the rural vote will\nbe in the minority for the first\ntime.\n10 Per Cent In Three Cities\nThe census, it appears upon\nIncomplete figures, will show\nmore than 34 per cent of the en\ntire population living in large\nCities. Approximately 10 per cent\nwill be shown to live in New\nYork, Chicago and Philadelphia\nAlone.\nThe first census in 1790 showed\nbut 3.3 per cent of the popula\ntion in cities over 8,000. In\n1880 the city population had\nreached 22.7 per cent and in\ncreased to 43.8 per cent in 1920.\nIndustry Attracts\nThe division of urban and\nrural population began with the\n1880 census. In 1880, 28.6 per\ncent of the pepole lived in towns\n\u2022nd cities of 2,500 or more; in\n1890, the figure was 35.4 per\ncent; in 1900 it rose to 40 per\ncent, in 1910 to 45.8 per cent,\nand ih 1920 to 51.4 per cent.\nThe greatest increases in popu\nlation reported are in large cities.\nThe smallest increases are re\nported from agricultural' States,\nexcept Florida.\nIt is not expected that the\npurely farm population of the\ncountry will show a decrease, but\nreturns now available make cer\ntain that surplus rural popula\ntion, as well as most immigration,\nis attracted by the industrial\ncenters.\nTrain Luneh Counter\n7-rr* 5 1... 1-\nIMII IF*\"\nJ -r ..Ji t fejj |gg\nI MKjia\nBF\nK k.\ngos Bl WHKbK\nK& &fIBL I K I\nBfe\\ jv s Iwl a.,---.-. 111\nn I.\u00a3 J|\nHH J \u00bb|iKl\u2018laH\nK I'l K-W 8 I B\n\u25a0Kliw W I\nIl 1 K-.-*'<:Xi\nllt I jjl I I\n\nHAVE A SANDWICH\nTHERE\u2019LL BE NO LAST CALL FOR DINNER on this\ncar. The Baltimore and Ohio soon will install a new\nluncheon car on its night Washington-New ,4fork trains.\nA special luncheon counter at one end of the coach will\n7/bmemacte \u2014Bat It\u2019s fteaZ /*an\nCLAIRE CORINNE\nSHHHr JHB\nsn li wlii\u2122\nI B J\nTimes Staff Photo\nMARY JULIANNE ZEPP\nJOHN E. ZEPP, 2550 Thirty-seventh St. N. W., has found away to keep his chil\ndren at home. He\u2019s built them a miniature playground, with a ferris wheel and every\nthing. Here\u2019s the wheel and here\u2019s the children.\nGAMP MEETING\nTO BE HELD\nLEESBURG, Va., July 30,-r-The\nannual Loudoun camp meeting\nwill be held, this year at Ben\nton\u2019s Camp Grounds, four miles\nnorth of Middleburg, Va., August\n10 to 24.\nThe association is planning to\nmake it a home-coming meeting\nin which the preachers who have\nbeen connected with the camp in\nformer years will take part.\nThere will be two religious ser\nvices. daily, at 11 a m. and 8\np. m. The music will be under\nthe leadership of Charles B.\nClArk, Roy\u2019 GoWley, pianist.\nThe committee of arrangements\nConsists of 'T. C. Iden, chair\nman; H. H. Otley, secretary-treas\nurer, and H. R. Chamblln, man\nager.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nMans Purse Is Buried\nBy Groundhog; He\nDigs 3 Days\nRICHMOND, Va., July 30.\nHow a Tazewell county, Va.,\nfarmer recovered his pocket\nbook containing $72 in green\nbacks after three days \u201cdig\nging\u201d has been learned.\nC. W. Watson, of the Pisgah\nneighborhood, near Bluefield.\nVa., decided to lay his purse by\na stump, fearing he might lose\nit from his pocket. He wrap\nped it up in a bandana hand-*\nkerchief and placed some sticks\nover it.\nHe was never out of sight of\nthe stump, but that evening,\nwhen he went to get his pock\netbook, he found the purse\nmissing. On the following day\nhe returned to the scene and,\nafter searching, he found a\ngroundhog hole near-by.\nThat gave Watson an idea.\nHe started digging and on the\nthird day he found his purse\nand money far back under the\nground. The groundhog had\ndisappeared. The $72 was found\nintact.\nPLANS CRIPPLE CLINIC\nWINCHESTER, Va., July 30\nThe next free clinic for cripples\nwill be held at the offices of the\nDistrict Nurse Association, near\nthe court house, next Saturday,\nAugust 2, and will be in charge of\nDr. Allen F. Voshell, of the Uni\nversity of Virginia Hospital.\nI 9|'\" iSmcn\nK MBbWk\n-\u25a0i^. jU^< WBE\nWtu\u25a0 w'\u25a0\nJmHI- aA\nIKI\nz r y*' 14\nOFF FOR A CAT NAP\ndispense food all day.and night. The,coach is equipped\nwith special reclining chairs. Men\u2019s and women\u2019s smok\ning rooms and other tasteful appointments will help make\nthe traveler\u2019s lot an easy one.\nMILLER NAMED\nTREASURER\nRICHMOND, Va., July 30.-L.\nL. Miller, deputy treasurer of\nGiles county, was appointed\ntreasurer to succeed W W.\nWalker, who submitted his resig\nnation by mail to Circuit Judge\nA. C. Buchanan, circuit judge at\nTazewell, following a State .audi\ntor\u2019s report that his accounts\nshowed an apparent shortage of\n$99,632.33 in county funds and\n$483.18 in State funds.\nWalker was bonded for SIOO,-\n000 in behalf of the county. Ho\nhas maintained consistently that\nhe has not used, public funds\nand that a check of his private\naccounts will clear up the dis\ncrepancy.\nThe new treasurer was re\nquired to give a temporary bond\nof SIO,OOO and to supply bond of\n$150,000 within the next few\ndays.\nTwo representatives of the Fi\ndelity and Deposit Company of\nBaltimore, surety for Treasurer\nWalker, told county authorities\nthat their company will make\ngood any shortage in Walker\u2019s ac\ncounts to the limit of its liabil\nity, but requested time to permit\ntheir auditors to prove the cor\nrectness of the State\u2019s audit.\nBIG WHEAT CROP\nFAIRFAX, Va., July 30.\u2014A rec\nord crop of wheat was threshed\nout last week at Willowmere\nFarm, near Merrifield. The aver\nage yield for the whole planting\nwas 42.5 bushels per acre.\nnt M Orfy\nGANAOIANS OUE\nTO RETALIATE\nON TARIFF\nNew Conservative Governors\nExpected to Strike at U. S.\nBarrier; Britain Competes\nBy GEORGE R. HOLMES\nThe decisive victory won by\nthe Conservatives in the Cana\ndian election probably spells trou\nble for American business.\nThis was rather gloomily con\nceded here today by those offi\ncials who keep closely in touch\nwith Canadian conditions. Can\nada is America\u2019s greatest cus\ntomer.\nThe new American tariff law,\nthrowing up the highest barriers\nin history against Canadian\nproducts, was the principal issue\nin the Conservative-Liberal cam\npaign across the border. The\nprovinces displayed 'their resent\nment against it by turning out\nthe Government of Mackenzie\nKing, who was accused of main\ntaining a too complacent attitude\ntoward the new American law.\nRetaliation Due\nAdministration officials are\nanxiously awaiting the formation\nof the new Conservative govern\nment, headed by Richard B. Ben\nnett, and the announcement of\nhis policies.\nThat retaliatory tariff action is\nto be taken by the Bennett Gov\nernment against the United\nStates is commonly expected on\nall sides. The conservative\nspokesmen pledged as much dur\ning the campaign that preceded\nthe voting. Even the retaliation\ntaken by the now defeated King\ngovernment, effected through\ntemporary laws, was not consid\nered sufficient for the Canadians.\nEvidently, by the sentiment ex\npressed in their votes, they want\nmore drastic action.\nOur Best Buyer\nThe effects on Canadian-Ameri\ncan trade may well be very seri\nous. Canada is and has been for\nyears America's best customer.\nAlmost every year since the war\n$800,000,000 worth of American\nproducts have flowed across the\nborder, while about half as much,\nor $400,000,000, has come from\nCanada to the United States.\nThe trade balance in American\nfavor is roughly $400,000.000. a\nyear, and that has represented no\ninconsiderable factor in American\nprosperity.\nNews Print Leads\nFrom the United States Canada\nhas imported automobiles,\nmachinery, gasoline and oil, iron\nand steel products and cotton.\nIn return, the United States has\ntaken cattle, dairy products,\nwheat, lumber, wood-pulp and\nnetra-print. The last named is\nCanada\u2019s greatest export to the\nUnited States.\nIf Canada now proceeds under\nthe new government to erect\nhigher tariff barriers against\nAmerican automobiles, machinery,\noil, iron and steel and cotton it\nwill strike a serious blow at\nAmerican business at the very\ntime when the scramble for\nworld-markets is becoming more\nand more acute.\nBritain Competes\nGreat Britain, which already\nhas some preferential treatment\nin Canada, is launched upon a\ngreat campaign for trading\nwithin the empire. Almost every\nthing that America ships to\nCanada in great volume must\nmeet British products in compe\ntition.\nA new and retaliatory Canadian\ntariff system will not help Amer\nican products in that competi\ntion. That much is assured. And\nAdministration officials in Wash\nington, scanning the horizon for\nthe return of prosperity on this\nside of the border, do not view\nthe prospect with much satisfac\ntion.\nGrange Will Oppose\nMpunt Vernon Bond\nVa., July 30.\u2014\nS Mount Vernon Orange has voted\nto oppose the joint recommenda\ntion of the county school board\nand the county board of super-*\nvisors that a bond issue be au\nthorized in this district for the\nconstruction of four consolidated\nschool centers at Woodlawn. Pot\nters Hill, Franconia and Grove\nton.\nThe Grange will work instead\nfor two larger school plants to\nbe built at points to be decided,\non later. It was held that the\nlarger schools would better serve\nthe needs of this section than a\ngreater number of smaller and\nless adequately equipped centers.\nCHARLES R. DAVIS DIES\nEx-Representative Charles R.\nDavis of Minnesota, died here\nyesterday after a long illness. He\nwas 81 years old.\nDressedMbm\\\ntkistheVMllidlondMM\nAnd Albert Rassan de\naiming is synonymous\nwfth good tailoring.\nKKSSSE9993\nWEDNESDAY, JULY SO, IS3O\nI\" i'\nToo Hot for Chickens\nL.|. I- hi.\nJEAN FREEING TAKING TEMPERATURE\n\u2014w,. Hi iiniimii i i \u25a0\u25a0\u25a0i.\u2014\n\\V\nW a\\\\w wJi\nWf X OW \\WW\n'B b\n\u25a0P-s Bfe 1\n1 1 jjfflkW\nlmbl i jn bea\nMl' V M TEMPERATURE T\nOF HEM\nJjl IPS' ly\n-A 'Jr^.'\u25a0\u25a0'\nr>\nZ BMElfc V*\n_ s*<\u2022*\u2022\nIp V lA'*\np\nIK|&9H9' BPj, \u00bbV\u00bbW\"\u2018\nm ssmsH iXyH f \"IT''\ntemperature li\ngSa OF HEN HOUSE g\nM ?^Ty IO Q y,\nZ, :X-V**.. W\u00abR>\nw M -\u00bbw-.w\u00bb\nA MODEL HEN HOUSE\nTHE UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND is having bad\ntimes these days with its prize hens. A chicken has\na body temperature of 105 degrees and no sweet glands.\nWhen the temperature rises higher than that of a\nchicken\u2019s body, the fowl usually dies. Model chicken\nhouses, constructed in order to give the chickens a place\nof refuge in hot weather have failed. Temperatures in\nthe houses have been registering as high as 109 degrees.\nJean Freling, Maryland University student, shows how a\nchicken\u2019s temperature is taken.\nPICKPOCKETS GET $322\nPickpockets yesterday robbed\nJames M. Power. 4000 block New\nHampshire Ave. N. W\u201e of his\npurse containing 1122 and a\ndiamond engagement ring worth\n1200, while he was riding on a\nstreet car.\nf TONITE--AT 1\nI KAY SH IRLEYgB\nt Cltver Dancert UMaT\nMildred Milter\nW Sinoino tht I. Hl?\nJ Blurt I\u2019ou Lika KB 11 It*\nWALES FLIES TO BRUSSELS\nBRUSSELS, July 29 (\u00dcB.).\nThe Prince of Wales landed here\ntonight after a flight from Lon\nddh. He came to Belgium to at\ntend the centenary exhibition.\nEEid\njBSwSBSSBSS&ffI\n12AAEASJ0GET\nDRASTIC DAY\nTDY-DUTS\nPresident Demands Strict En\nforcement in Attempt to\nSee If Law Is Workable\nComplete reorganization of dry\nlaw enforcement personnel was de\ncided \u00fcbon at a conference yester\nday between President Hoover, At\ntorney General Mitchell. Assistant\nAttorney General Youngquist and\nAmos W. W. Woodcock, prohibit\ntion director.\nThe plan win be launched to\nday when Mitchell, with Wood\ncock and his aides, meet with the\nprohibition administrators from\nthe 12 districts, the first meeting\nsince enforcement was transferred\nfrom the Treasury to the Depart\nment of Justice.\nAffect All Districts\nThe President discussed in de\ntail the recommendations of the\nspecial commission on law enforce\nment and observance.\nJust how extensive the changes\nwill be the White House declined\nto say. It .was made plain, how\never, that they would affect every\ndistrict and community in the\ncountry and the border as well as\ncoast patrol.\nIt was indicated that there\nare to be many changes in the\nadministration. These, it was\nstated, will be where an admin\nistrator has been found better\nsuited for direction instead of\nfield work, and where new di\nvisions are to be created for\nthe better regulation of indus\ntrial alcohol and breweries.\nSpecial Message\nThe President, it is under\ni stood, will send a special mes\nsage to the administrators in\nwhich he will tell them that he\nexpects to see the new dry\nunit launch upon a campaign\nof drastic law enforcement and\nput to the supreme test the\nquestion of whether or not the\ndry law can be enforced.\nThe dry enforcement will also\nbe decentralized to a large ex\ntent, it was learned, with the\nadministrators given wide au\nthority in their various dis\ntricts to replace enforcement\nagents and completely reorgan\nize their immediate offices and\ndistricts.\nHistoric Mansion\nIs Being Restored\nSTRASBURG. Va.. July 30.\u2014\nThe historic Bell Grove mansion\nthree miles north of Strasburg\nowned at present by F. W. Hun\nnewell. secretary to the president\nof Harvard University, is being\nentirely restored to the original\ndesign made by Thomas Jeffer\nson for Major Isaac Hite, when\nhe built it in 1787 for his wife.\nNellie Conway Madison, sister of\nPresident Madison.\nThe work is in charge of Det\nlow M. MArthinson, structural en\ngineer: Horace W. Peaslie, archi\ntect and Henry H. Shufeldt,\nsuperintendent.\nJ 11 L r\nr 1! I\n/i wIS Bl\nI\nf JKaiUML I\nI B\n1-\nI\n\n\n\n\\^SlL s M\nEXACTING!\nDeal\u2019s code of service is an ex\nacting one, and every employe\nknows that unselfish devotion\nmust at all imes be paramount\nComplete Funeral\n$125-p\nA $225 Deal Complete\nFuneral Includes:\nA. black broadcloth casket,\nwith Bilk interior and six very\n-fine handles (thia casket alone\nsells tor 1150); engraved name\nplate; number 1 white pine out\nside ease, embalming, washing,\ndressing, shaving if necessary,\n\u2019advertising the death, removing\nfrom hospital, crepe for the door,\nrugs, chairs, gloves, hearse and\ntwo Cadillac seven-passenger\nlimousines./*.\nWhen !n need of. our Service\nCall the Deal Funeral Home.\nFor reference ask \u201cyout; neigh\nbor.\u201d\nLincoln 8200-8201\nDeal Funeral Home\n818 H Street N. E.","height":"30530","width":"24457"}}
